<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-137-082 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 846 302</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommuting Review: the Gordon Report  June 1 1991 v8 n6 p1(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Telecommuting applications: Utah data entry firm thrives withtelecommuters while serving large companies' needs. (interviewwith Unibase Data Entry co-founder Lynn Blodgett) (interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Staker, Dorine.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Salt Lake City, UT, data entry firm Unibase Data Entry (UDE)co-founder Lynn Blodgett describes the telecommuting operations ofher firm.andP;  UDE provides data entry services to large companies whodo not have sufficient in-house staff to handle excess paperwork.andO;The data entry firm has about 500 employees, 386 of whom aretelecommuting.andP;  It has also set up telecommuting operations inmost of the state prisons in the US.andP;  The UDE telecommutingoperation is run by one supervisor and eight assistants.andP;  Thetelecommuters themselves are 99 percent female , 93 percentmarried, 95 percent 20 to 35 years old, with almost 90 percenthaving pre-school children, and 80 percent selecting telecommutingto be able to stay at home with their children.andP;  The firm providesup to ten weeks of training, and a good worker can average$6-to-$8 per hour on the piecework pay rates, which vary dependingon the client.andP;  The low turnover and financial advantages oftelecommuting to UDE's workers are also discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Unibase Data Entry Inc. (Management).andO;Topic:     TelecommutingData EntryCompaniesInterviewCase StudyCompany ProfileGrowthCost Benefit Analysis.andO;Person:    Blodgett, Lynn (Interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>